Figure 5 shows the inferred infection rate, death rate and the recovery rate of the inferred model for Mexico. We can clearly see the spreading of the disease from Mexico City. Similar to the case of Michigan, infection rates, and to a lesser extent, death rates, were relatively lower in Mexico City, which is the most densely populated region of the country, than that in the surrounding cities. The recovery rate was high in Mexico city, in part due to the relatively greater resources of the medical system there. The infection and death rates tended to be stable for five months following March 23, 2020, and the recovery rate gradually increased in more areas. Notably, far from the Mexico city, Baja California also displayed a high inferred rate of infection. We suspect this to be because it borders California, USA, and the international border restrictions did not contain the spread of the virus between the two regions. Unlike Mexico City, the death rate remained high, and the recovery rate did not increase to levels comparable to the capital, perhaps because of the looser restrictions in this popular tourist destination. The reproduction number \documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
